Hey team 👋

Most of us have been working closely with LLMs — feeding JSON configs, API responses, schema files, and sample payloads into ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, and similar tools.

By now, we have all felt the same friction: large JSON files consume a lot of context window space, not because of the actual data, but because of structural noise — brackets, quotes, commas, and repeated key names across every array row.

I know there are already many extensions and tools available in the market for JSON formatting, minifying, and conversion. But this extension is different. It is focused specifically on **LLM-friendly token optimization** — helping developers convert JSON into a more compact format that reduces unnecessary token usage while keeping the data readable and useful for AI tools.

That is where **TOON — Token-Optimized Object Notation** — comes in.

TOON is a compact, human-readable format that removes unnecessary overhead while keeping every value intact and easy for the model to understand.

I built a VS Code extension around it:

**JSON to TOON Converter v1.0.2**

The goal is simple: convert JSON to TOON directly inside VS Code without relying on external websites or third-party tools.

Everything runs natively inside VS Code.
Your data never leaves your machine.

## What it does

It converts JSON into TOON — a compact, quote-free format that cuts structural noise:

No repeated brackets.
No redundant key names across every row.
No unnecessary surrounding quotes.

## Real benchmark from the extension

**JSON:** 665 characters / ~92 tokens
**TOON:** 237 characters / ~41 tokens

That is around **55% fewer tokens** with the same data.

For large API responses, deeply nested config files, or schema-heavy JSON, the savings can be even more useful.

## Three ways to use it inside VS Code

**1. CodeLens**
A **Convert to TOON** link appears inline above line 1 of any JSON file. Just click it.

**2. Right-click menu**
Works in both the editor and Explorer panel.
Right-click any `.json` file and choose **Convert to TOON**.

**3. Command Palette**
Use `Ctrl + Shift + P` or `Cmd + Shift + P`, then run **Convert to TOON**.

